===''Kids React''=== Benny and Rafi Fine launched a series titled ''Kids React'' on October 16, 2010, the first video being "Kids React to Viral Videos (''[[Double Rainbow (viral video)|Double Rainbow]]'', Obama Fail, Twin Rabbits, [[Snickers]] [[Halloween]])".{{sfn|Jaworski|2013}} The ''Kids React'' series features The Fine Brothers, off-camera, showing kids ages 4–14 (7-13 as of September 2016, 7-11 as of October 2016) several viral videos or popular YouTubers and having the kids react to the videos.{{sfn|Hallam|2010}}{{sfn|O'Neill|2010}}{{sfn|"Kids React to Epic Meal Time"|2011}}{{sfn|Whitney|2012}}
The most popular ''Kids React'' episode to date is “Kids React to Gay Marriage", with over 40.2 million views as of September 2, 2018. The popularity of ''Kids React'' made it possible for the online series to win a special [[Emmy Award]] at the [[39th Daytime Emmy Awards]] in 2012.{{sfn|Hernandez|2012}} The Emmy Award, that was given in cooperation with [[AOL]], was awarded to the Fine Brothers for "Best Viral Video Series".{{sfn|Paredes|2012}} After their Emmy win, the brothers stated, "Not a lot has changed [after winning the Emmy] other than realizing that there are shows on YouTube like ''React'' that can get similar if not better viewership than mainstream entertainment can."{{sfn|Jaworski|2013}}
Videos and YouTube stars that have been reacted to by the kids include [[Smosh]] (who later reacted to the kids' reactions{{sfn|"Smosh Reacts"|2011}}), [[planking (fad)|planking]]{{sfn|Chansanchai|2011}} and [[Barack Obama|President Obama]] [[Death of Osama bin Laden#U.S. presidential address|addressing the death of]] [[Osama bin Laden]],{{sfn|Choi|2011}}{{sfn|Hustvedt|2011}} among several other topics.{{sfn|Johnson|2011}}{{sfn|Idolator Staff|2011}} ''Kids React'' has been compared to ''[[Kids Say the Darndest Things]]''.{{sfn|Brustein|2014}}{{sfn|Sullivan|2011}} In October 2012, the kids of the show were shown videos of the [[United States presidential election debates, 2012|2012 U.S. Presidential debates]].{{sfn|Von Baldegg|2012}} ''Kids React'' won the Streamy Award for Best Non-Fiction or Reality Series in 2013.{{sfn|"Pre-Live Streamy Winners Announced"|2013}}
===''Teens React''=== Due to the popularity of ''Kids React'', The Fine Brothers spawned a spin-off dubbed ''Teens React'' on November 17, 2011 with "TEENS REACT TO [[The Twilight Saga (film series)|TWILIGHT]]".{{sfn|O'Neill|2011}} The show has a similar premise to ''Kids React'', however the younger stars are replaced with teens, some of whom have aged out of the ''Kids React'' series. Due to this, the Fine Brothers are able to show more mature and less "kid-friendly" videos such as videos on topics like ''[[Toddlers & Tiaras]]'',{{sfn|Chansanchai|2012}} [[Rick Perry]]'s ''[[Rick Perry presidential campaign, 2012#Appeals to Christian voters|Strong]]'' commercial,{{sfn|Frauenfelder|2011}} [[Suicide of Amanda Todd|Amanda Todd's death]],{{sfn|Lum|2012}} and the [[United States presidential election debates, 2012|2012 U.S. Presidential debates]]. Other viral videos and YouTube stars that have been reacted to include ''[[Salad Fingers]]'', the ''[[Overly Attached Girlfriend]]'', "[[Gangnam Style]]", ''[[The Hunger Games (film)|The Hunger Games]]'' trailer,{{sfn|Johnson|2012}} [[Shane Dawson]],{{sfn|"Shane Dawson: Watch Teens Reacting"|2012}} and [[One Direction]],{{sfn|Orenstein|2012}} among other topics. Later on The Fine Brothers launched a series named ''Teens React: Gaming'' consisting videos of teens reacting to popular games such as ''[[Mario Kart 64]], [[Flappy Bird]]'', and ''[[Rocket League]]''.{{sfn|Hilliard|2015}} Teens React launched the career of [[Lia Marie Johnson]] and also featured some "famous" 'reactors' as guest stars, including [[Lisa Cimorelli]], [[Amy Cimorelli]], [[Lucas Cruikshank]] (who later appears in Youtubers React), [[Alex Steele]], [[Jake Short]], and [[Maisie Williams]].{{sfn|Moran|2015}}
===''Elders React''=== The popularity of ''Kids React'' and ''Teens React'' spawned ''Elders React'' on May 24, 2012 with "ELDERS REACT TO NYAN CAT". The Elders React series replaces young children and teenagers with the elderly, including Benny and Rafi's father, Yehuda.{{sfn|"Elders React To Skrillex"|2012}} Initially starting with topics that have been discussed on the other ''React'' series, they currently discuss about topics that appeals to today's 21st century society such as violent video games and music videos.
===''YouTubers React''=== The first episode of ''YouTubers React'' premiered December 6, 2012. The first episode was "YouTubers React to Viral Videos Ep. #1". Several notable YouTubers have appeared on the series.{{sfn|Gutelle|2012}} [[Tay Zonday]], [[Rebecca Black]] and [[Liam Kyle Sullivan]] have each reacted to one of their own videos, "[[Chocolate Rain]]," "[[Friday (Rebecca Black song)|Friday]]" and "[[Shoes (Kelly song)|Shoes]]" respectively.{{sfn|Dreier|2013}}
===''Adults React''=== On May 30, 2015, the Fine Brothers announced ''Adults React'', which premiered on July 16 later that year. It consists of people ages 20 to 55, including former stars of ''Teens React'' that have aged out of the series. Depending on the video or topic, ''Adults React'' will be specific of which type of adults are going to be reacting, such as parents or young adults.{{sfn|Fine Brothers|2015}}
===''College Kids React''=== The first episode of ''College Kids React'' premiered on June 23, 2016 with "College Kids React to [[The 1975]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ufwfMo4BRak|title=College Kids React to The 1975|publisher=Fine Brothers Entertainment|website=[[YouTube]]|date=June 23, 2016}}</ref> This series includes stars who have aged out of ''Teens React'' alongside new stars, as well as stars that have not yet aged out of ''Teens React'' but have begun college. The content of ''College Kids React'' is similar to the content found in ''Teens React''.
===One-off episodes=== In April 2014, as an [[April Fool's]] joke, the Fine Brothers teamed up with [[Friskies]] and released ''Cats React'', which went viral.{{sfn|Cohen|2014}} In July 2016 they released another part of ''Cats React''.
In August 2014, they released ''Celebrities React to Viral Videos''.
In April 2018, an another April Fools’s joke, they released ‘’Teens React to Nothing’’ where they showed teens a blank screen.
==React YouTube channel== After creating four individual successful ''React'' series on their primary YouTube channel, the Fine Brothers launched a separate YouTube channel in 2014, for reaction-related content, simply dubbed "React".{{sfn|Spangler|2014}} With the intent of running programming five days a week,{{sfn|Spangler|2014}} the channel launched with five series: ''Games'' (a [[Let's Play (video gaming)|Let's Play]] style series with cast members from their primary ''React'' series), ''Advice'' (a series featuring cast members respond to questions from viewers), ''React Remix'' (musical remixes of past ''React'' footage), ''People Vs. Foods'' (a series featuring Reactors taste test "Weird" or international foods), and ''Lyric Breakdown'' (a series in which Reactors break down the meaning of various songs).{{sfn|Gutelle|2014}} The channel launched with a teen-centered playthrough of ''[[Goat Simulator]]''.{{sfn|Van Winkle|2014}} Similar to the teens, the elders also have played and reacted to video games such as ''[[Grand Theft Auto V]]'', ''[[Call of Duty: Advanced Warfare]]'' and ''[[Call of Duty: Black Ops II]]''. Kids and Adults also played and reacted to video games too.{{sfn|Farokhmanesh|2015}}
==''React to That''== In early 2014, it was announced that the Fine Brothers made a deal with Ncredible Entertainment, a production studio founded by [[Nick Cannon]] to develop a television series for [[Nickelodeon]].{{sfn|Patel|2014}} The series, dubbed ''[[React to That]]'', was "entirely re-envisioned for television," as the reactors "not only watch and respond to viral videos, but pop out of the reaction room and into showdowns where the clips come to life as each reactor is confronted with a challenge based on the video they just watched."{{sfn|Block|2014}} Following the announcement of the series, Benny Fine stated, "All these viewers now watching are also pioneering what it is to be a viewer of content. They follow us through all of our different endeavors, all our different series, and now will have the opportunity to follow us to another medium."{{sfn|Block|2014}} Nickelodeon ordered 13 episodes to be produced,{{sfn|Block|2014}} but only 12 were made and aired.{{sfn|Spangler|2016}}
==React World==
===Background=== In July 2015, the Fine Brothers filed for trademark protection on "React" with the [[U.S. Patent and Trademark Office]] (USPTO).{{sfn|Spangler|2016}} The trademark was filed for "Entertainment services, namely, providing an ongoing series of programs and webisodes via the internet in the field of observing and interviewing various groups of people."{{sfn|Hern|2016}} The USPTO approved for a 30-day opposition period which was set to begin on February 2, 2016; if no parties filed an opposition to the Fines' trademark request, it would have proceeded through the process.{{sfn|Machkovech|2016}} The brothers had previously filed for and been granted trademark registrations for "Elders React" and "Teens React" in 2013 as well as "Kids React" in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|title = A Fine mess: how not to assert your copyright in the YouTube age|url = https://www.theverge.com/2016/2/6/10926230/fine-bros-react-world-controversy|website = The Verge|access-date = February 18, 2016}}</ref>
===Announcement details=== On January 26, 2016, the Fines announced that they would be launching React World, a way to grant content creators the license to create their own versions of the ''React'' shows.{{sfn|Spangler|2016}}{{sfn|Fine Brothers|2016a}} Specifically, the Fine Brothers stated they are licensing the format of their ''React'' shows.{{sfn|Hamedy|2016}} A ''Variety'' report detailed that React World would "aggregate videos in a channel to launch later this year to promote, support and feature fan-produced programming based on their shows."{{sfn|Spangler|2016}} The brothers' company, Fine Brothers Entertainment (FBE) stated they would be working with YouTube and ChannelMeter on the launch of React World.{{sfn|Shah|2016}} FBE also expressed they would be able to monetize ''React''-style videos uploaded under their license.{{sfn|Spangler|2016}}{{sfn|Fine Brothers|2016a}} On monetization, ''Digital Trends'' detailed "Although licenses are free, React World creators must agree to share 20 percent of AdSense revenue and 30 percent of premium brand deals with FBE."{{sfn|Shah|2016}} Additionally, the Fines stated they will provide ongoing production guidance, creative guidelines, format bibles, and other resources, as well as promotional and technical support to those creators who participated with the brothers on React World.{{sfn|Shah|2016}}
===Reception=== Although YouTube's VP on content partnerships, Kelly Merryman, originally proclaimed "This is brand-building in the YouTube age — rising media companies building their brands through collaborations with creators around the world,"{{sfn|Spangler|2016}} the Fine Brothers were met with overwhelmingly negative reception to their React World announcement.{{sfn|Hamedy|2016}}{{sfn|Shah|2016}}{{sfn|Baker-Whitelaw|2016}} ''[[BBC News]]'' reported that "critics of the Fine Brothers have expressed concern they may use the trademarks to stifle competition," and quoted one YouTuber who detailed "People don't trust them because a few years ago when [[Ellen DeGeneres]] did a similar video—not that similar, it didn't have the same format or branding—they claimed it was their format."{{sfn|Foxx|2016}} Viewers and fellow content creators alike condemned the Fines for their announcement, with ''[[The Daily Dot]]'' reporting, "Backlash poured in on [[Reddit]] and social media, and other YouTubers posted their own reactions and parodies of the enthusiastically corporate React World announcement video."{{sfn|Baker-Whitelaw|2016}} The backlash led to a dramatic drop in subscribers,{{sfn|Mooney|2016}} with upwards of 675,000{{#tag:ref|As of February 22, 2016. Not including positive subs counts.|group = "n"}} accounts collectively unsubscribing from the React and Fine Bros Entertainment channels as well as recent videos getting many dislikes in [[protest]] as of February 22, 2016.<ref name="fbe30days">{{cite web|title=Fine Brothers Entertainment 30 days|url=http://socialblade.com/youtube/user/thefinebros/monthly|website=Social Blade|publisher=Maker Studio|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref><ref name="rc30days">{{cite web|title=React Channel 30 Days|url=http://socialblade.com/youtube/user/react/monthly|website=Social Blade|publisher=Makers Studio|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref>{{sfn|"Fine Brothers Entertainment"|n.d.}} ''[[Mashable]]'' described that one Reddit post "ignited a thread of haters, defenders and overall discussion about whether what Fine Brothers Entertainment is doing is fair."{{sfn|Hamedy|2016}} [[Ryan Morrison]], a gamer, lawyer and Reddit user, declared that he would file a legal challenge to the Fine Brothers' trademark request on "React", writing "These guys didn’t come up with the idea of filming funny reactions from kids. And they certainly don’t own an entire genre of YouTube videos. It wasn’t their idea, and it’s not theirs to own or police."{{sfn|Hathaway|2016}}
Though there was an overwhelmingly negative response to the React World announcement, other personalities expressed milder opinions; Internet personality [[Hank Green]] wrote "this could actually be a very cool project if it could be divorced from the idea of two very powerful creators attempting to control a very popular YouTube video format. Franchising one of YouTube's biggest shows? Yeah, I’d love to see how that goes."{{sfn|Hathaway|2016}} ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' reporter Jay Hathaway wrote "The trademark and React World are dead. And that's a shame, because it was an interesting idea that suffered from tone-deaf execution."{{sfn|Hathaway|2016}}
===Responses and discontinuation by the Fine Brothers=== After seeing the initial backlash from their announcement, The Fine Brothers posted comments on various social media websites including [[Facebook]], [[Twitter]], Reddit, and the comment section of their YouTube announcement video.{{sfn|Hamedy|2016}} On Facebook the Fines wrote, "We do not own the idea or copyright for reaction videos overall, nor did we ever say we did. You don’t need anyone’s permission to make these kinds of videos, and we’re not coming after anyone," adding "We are in no way claiming reaction content in general is our intellectual property. This is purely a voluntary program for people wanting direct support from us, and we continue to be so excited to work with all of you who may want to participate."{{sfn|Baker-Whitelaw|2016}}{{sfn|Fine Brothers|2016a}} They additionally tweeted "We're not saying we hold a copyright on reaction videos overall, no one can. We're licensing our specific shows, like TV has done for years."{{sfn|Hamedy|2016}} The brothers also stated they would "not be trying to take revenue from other types of reaction videos, and will not be copyright-striking."{{sfn|Hamedy|2016}} However, other YouTubers have reported multiple copyright related video takedowns.{{sfn|8-Bit Eric|2016}}{{sfn|LeKevPlays|2016}} ''[[The Guardian]]'' also reported that unrelated channels featuring other groups of people reacting to videos were also removed after takedown requests from the Fine Brothers; the "Seniors React" video was noted to be released prior to the Fines launching their ''Elders React'' series.{{sfn|Hern|2016}} The Fines also posted an update video in response to what they described as "confusion and negative response" to React World, in which they try to clear up confusion on what their format encompasses, as well as inviting viewers to e-mail them about any further questions.{{sfn|Baker-Whitelaw|2016}}
Ultimately, the Fine Brothers removed all React World videos,{{sfn|Yin-Poole|2016}} and posted a statement on ''[[Medium (website)|Medium]]'', declaring they have filed the paperwork to [[Rescission (contract law)|rescind]] all their "React" trademarks and applications, will discontinue the React World program, and will release all past Content ID claims.{{sfn|Fine Brothers|2016b}} In their post, the brothers expressed "It makes perfect sense for people to distrust our motives here, but we are confident that our actions will speak louder than these words moving forward."{{sfn|Rundle|2016}} Reaction to this ''Medium'' post was negative on Reddit, where users were reported commenting they would not forgive the Fine Brothers.{{sfn|Rundle|2016}}
